WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.840
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:05.935 --> 00:00:07.060
MALIKA SAADA SAAR: Welcome.

00:00:07.060 --> 00:00:09.150
My name is Malika Saada Saar.

00:00:09.150 --> 00:00:13.380
I'm Google's Senior Council
on Civil and Human Rights.

00:00:13.380 --> 00:00:18.050
You know, about a year ago,
the great human rights lawyer

00:00:18.050 --> 00:00:21.540
Brian Stevenson came to Google.

00:00:21.540 --> 00:00:24.870
Came to our TGIF,
where all of us

00:00:24.870 --> 00:00:26.580
come together in Mountain View.

00:00:26.580 --> 00:00:30.610
And TGIF is livestreamed
to all of our employees.

00:00:30.610 --> 00:00:35.580
And so, as a company, we came
together to welcome Brian.

00:00:35.580 --> 00:00:41.580
And Brian said to us,
challenged us, to bear witness,

00:00:41.580 --> 00:00:47.740
to be proximate to the human
costs of mass incarceration.

00:00:47.740 --> 00:00:52.260
And so over the year,
in the last 10 months,

00:00:52.260 --> 00:00:56.010
in fact, we have been doing
criminal justice forums

00:00:56.010 --> 00:00:59.100
within Google to
really do what Brian

00:00:59.100 --> 00:01:02.580
asks us to do-- to
bear witness and to be

00:01:02.580 --> 00:01:07.110
proximate to the human
costs of mass incarceration.

00:01:07.110 --> 00:01:11.640
We've had these conversations in
different parts of our company.

00:01:11.640 --> 00:01:16.020
We've thought about and continue
to ask the question of--

00:01:16.020 --> 00:01:22.170
how do we use our platforms
to disrupt mass incarceration?

00:01:22.170 --> 00:01:25.770
Because we know that what
we do at Google is disrupt,

00:01:25.770 --> 00:01:27.420
disrupt for good.

00:01:27.420 --> 00:01:30.050
And if anything needs
to be disrupted,

00:01:30.050 --> 00:01:32.250
its the overcriminalization
of our black

00:01:32.250 --> 00:01:34.830
and brown communities.

00:01:34.830 --> 00:01:38.180
But most of how we've
had that conversation

00:01:38.180 --> 00:01:41.510
has really been
without the words

00:01:41.510 --> 00:01:44.840
and lived experiences
of women and girls.

00:01:44.840 --> 00:01:48.950
And so today, as part of
Women's History Month,

00:01:48.950 --> 00:01:52.460
we want to be able
to delve deeply

00:01:52.460 --> 00:01:57.440
into what is mass incarceration
from the perspective of women

00:01:57.440 --> 00:01:58.370
and girls?

00:01:58.370 --> 00:02:01.590
When we talk about
achieving racial justice,

00:02:01.590 --> 00:02:05.910
how do we do it from
a gendered lens?

00:02:05.910 --> 00:02:08.840
Up to 80% of women
behind bars have

00:02:08.840 --> 00:02:13.150
been subject to some
form of sexual violence.

00:02:13.150 --> 00:02:16.380
Sexual violence is
the primary predictor

00:02:16.380 --> 00:02:19.290
of girls going behind bars.

00:02:19.290 --> 00:02:22.710
And women and girls are
the fastest growing prison

00:02:22.710 --> 00:02:24.300
populations.

00:02:24.300 --> 00:02:27.090
We must have this
conversation as part

00:02:27.090 --> 00:02:32.080
of our overall commitment to
disrupting mass incarceration.

00:02:32.080 --> 00:02:37.020
We cannot have any real
comprehensive discourse around

00:02:37.020 --> 00:02:41.430
criminalization of black and
brown communities without

00:02:41.430 --> 00:02:46.290
centering the experiences
of women and girls.

00:02:46.290 --> 00:02:50.280
And with that, it is my
absolute honor and privilege

00:02:50.280 --> 00:02:54.300
to introduce to you the
founder and Executive Director

00:02:54.300 --> 00:02:57.060
of the National
Council for Formerly

00:02:57.060 --> 00:03:00.780
Incarcerated and Incarcerated
Women and Girls, Andrea James.

00:03:00.780 --> 00:03:06.744
[APPLAUSE]

00:03:06.744 --> 00:03:07.910
ANDREA JAMES: Hi, everybody.

00:03:07.910 --> 00:03:08.690
Thank you.

00:03:08.690 --> 00:03:12.580
I'm not going to be labor
anything beyond what Malika

00:03:12.580 --> 00:03:13.880
has said.

00:03:13.880 --> 00:03:16.910
I cannot underscore enough the
importance of the words that

00:03:16.910 --> 00:03:17.540
she did say.

00:03:17.540 --> 00:03:20.450
I want to say thank you to
everybody here at Google, both

00:03:20.450 --> 00:03:23.720
in this room, and those of
you who are on live stream,

00:03:23.720 --> 00:03:26.930
for tuning in to this
incredibly important issue.

00:03:26.930 --> 00:03:28.970
And I think, without
me going any further,

00:03:28.970 --> 00:03:30.650
you will understand
why it was so

00:03:30.650 --> 00:03:34.160
important by the end of
our time here together.

00:03:34.160 --> 00:03:35.792
Miss Alice, are you there?

00:03:35.792 --> 00:03:37.250
ALICE MARIE JOHNSON:
Yes, I'm here.

00:03:37.250 --> 00:03:39.440
ANDREA JAMES: Can
you see me at all?

00:03:39.440 --> 00:03:40.760
ALICE MARIE JOHNSON: No,
I don't see you right now.

00:03:40.760 --> 00:03:42.200
ANDREA JAMES: OK,
well, I love you.

00:03:42.200 --> 00:03:43.385
I don't know what
I'm doing here.

00:03:43.385 --> 00:03:43.860
ALICE MARIE JOHNSON:
I love you, too.

00:03:43.860 --> 00:03:44.359
Thank you.

00:03:44.359 --> 00:03:46.520
ANDREA JAMES: Topeka's
telling me to do something--

00:03:46.520 --> 00:03:47.050
what phone?

00:03:47.050 --> 00:03:47.800
Oh, here.

00:03:47.800 --> 00:03:48.740
Hi, Miss Alice.

00:03:48.740 --> 00:03:49.910
There you go.

00:03:49.910 --> 00:03:51.770
ALICE MARIE JOHNSON:
Oh, I see you now.

00:03:51.770 --> 00:03:52.540
Hi, Andrea.

00:03:52.540 --> 00:03:53.998
ANDREA JAMES: How
are you, darling?

00:03:53.998 --> 00:03:56.800
OK, so we're going to
begin our conversation.

00:03:56.800 --> 00:04:00.637
You are seeing Miss
Alice Marie Johnson.

00:04:00.637 --> 00:04:02.720
And I'm going to tell you
very briefly, so that we

00:04:02.720 --> 00:04:04.070
can get to Ms.
Johnson, and you're

00:04:04.070 --> 00:04:06.028
going to hear from her
for the rest of the time

00:04:06.028 --> 00:04:08.330
that we're having our
discussion together,

00:04:08.330 --> 00:04:10.980
about the work of
the National Council.

00:04:10.980 --> 00:04:15.380
We are a platform that we have
created, really starting out.

00:04:15.380 --> 00:04:19.070
Because we knew that our
voices needed to be heard.

00:04:19.070 --> 00:04:21.470
Our mantra is nothing
about us without us.

00:04:21.470 --> 00:04:24.230
Because we are the experts,
the women and girls who

00:04:24.230 --> 00:04:26.300
have gone through
the experiences, who

00:04:26.300 --> 00:04:30.260
have been directly affected by
an incredibly unjust, racist,

00:04:30.260 --> 00:04:33.950
classist, and discriminatory
criminal justice system,

00:04:33.950 --> 00:04:37.040
we are the experts that
need to be at the forefront

00:04:37.040 --> 00:04:39.950
and at the table in
creating a policy for--

00:04:39.950 --> 00:04:42.560
not just change, not for
reforming a criminal justice

00:04:42.560 --> 00:04:46.160
system that we don't believe
can be reformed, but in creating

00:04:46.160 --> 00:04:50.684
and shifting radically
to a human justice system

00:04:50.684 --> 00:04:51.600
and what that entails.

00:04:51.600 --> 00:04:53.270
So the National Council
for Incarcerated

00:04:53.270 --> 00:04:55.340
and Formerly Incarcerated
Women and Girls

00:04:55.340 --> 00:04:58.850
was created to connect all
of the powerful, brilliant,

00:04:58.850 --> 00:05:03.470
courageous, brave, incarcerated
and formerly incarcerated women

00:05:03.470 --> 00:05:05.600
and girls across
this country who

00:05:05.600 --> 00:05:08.060
are doing that
work as the experts

00:05:08.060 --> 00:05:11.240
to create the change that
we know needs to happen.

00:05:11.240 --> 00:05:14.180
You're going to hear from
many of them here today.

00:05:14.180 --> 00:05:17.690
And you are privileged to have
the voice of the experience

00:05:17.690 --> 00:05:20.150
of the women that you will
hear from today, starting

00:05:20.150 --> 00:05:21.560
with Miss Alice.

00:05:21.560 --> 00:05:24.170
And the Obama
administration started

00:05:24.170 --> 00:05:26.780
a project called The
Clemency Project 2014,

00:05:26.780 --> 00:05:29.390
obviously it was back in 2014.

00:05:29.390 --> 00:05:31.910
And we went to the mat,
under the leadership

00:05:31.910 --> 00:05:35.340
of our clemency
expert, Amy Povah, who

00:05:35.340 --> 00:05:38.360
was a woman who served years
in the federal prison system

00:05:38.360 --> 00:05:41.690
prior to her sentence being
commuted by President Bill

00:05:41.690 --> 00:05:42.560
Clinton.

00:05:42.560 --> 00:05:45.410
And Amy, we have this thing,
when we leave the prison doors,

00:05:45.410 --> 00:05:49.460
and we're walking out the door,
everybody says don't look back.

00:05:49.460 --> 00:05:50.480
Don't look back.

00:05:50.480 --> 00:05:51.530
It's like a curse.

00:05:51.530 --> 00:05:52.670
Don't look back.

00:05:52.670 --> 00:05:53.314
We love you.

00:05:53.314 --> 00:05:54.230
We want to see you go.

00:05:54.230 --> 00:05:55.340
Do not look back.

00:05:55.340 --> 00:05:57.110
If you look back,
it's like the curse

00:05:57.110 --> 00:05:58.340
is going to bring you back.

00:05:58.340 --> 00:06:00.680
And so we kind of leave
there, and we don't look back.

00:06:00.680 --> 00:06:01.910
Amy Povah looked back.

00:06:01.910 --> 00:06:03.950
She never stopped
looking back from the day

00:06:03.950 --> 00:06:06.680
that she left that prison when
President Bill Clinton commuted

00:06:06.680 --> 00:06:07.460
her sentence.

00:06:07.460 --> 00:06:10.600
She started the organization
Can Do Clemency.

00:06:10.600 --> 00:06:11.900
And please, check it out.

00:06:11.900 --> 00:06:14.100
You are going to see some
of the faces of the women,

00:06:14.100 --> 00:06:16.370
including Miss Alice
that are part of that.

00:06:16.370 --> 00:06:18.710
Well, unfortunately
or fortunately,

00:06:18.710 --> 00:06:21.740
of the very small
number of the thousands

00:06:21.740 --> 00:06:25.670
of women that met
President Obama's criteria,

00:06:25.670 --> 00:06:29.120
but somehow were left
behind, 50 of our women

00:06:29.120 --> 00:06:32.240
did make it out under the
leadership of Amy Povah

00:06:32.240 --> 00:06:34.550
and the women of the
council and women

00:06:34.550 --> 00:06:36.920
across this country that
went to the mat to fight,

00:06:36.920 --> 00:06:39.050
to push these women
out of prison.

00:06:39.050 --> 00:06:43.490
Miss Alice Johnson fit those
criteria, unfortunately,

00:06:43.490 --> 00:06:45.950
and even though she's been
in a prison for decades,

00:06:45.950 --> 00:06:50.090
was not one of the women that
we were able to push out.

00:06:50.090 --> 00:06:53.124
And this is incredibly
painful for us.

00:06:53.124 --> 00:06:54.290
And I'm going to stop there.

00:06:54.290 --> 00:06:55.670
And I'm going to
ask Miss Alice--

00:06:55.670 --> 00:06:57.470
Miss Alice, we love you.

00:06:57.470 --> 00:06:58.916
We understand how incredible--

00:06:58.916 --> 00:07:00.290
Miss Alice is in
a federal prison

00:07:00.290 --> 00:07:02.060
speaking to us right now.

00:07:02.060 --> 00:07:05.510
And I want you to begin, Miss
Alice, by telling us about you

00:07:05.510 --> 00:07:07.220
and about your
story, and why you're

00:07:07.220 --> 00:07:09.920
sitting in that federal prison.

00:07:09.920 --> 00:07:10.941
ALICE MARIE JOHNSON: OK.

00:07:10.941 --> 00:07:11.440
OK.

00:07:11.440 --> 00:07:14.150
My name is Alice Marie Johnson.

00:07:14.150 --> 00:07:18.530
And on May 30th of this
year, I'll be 62-years-old.

00:07:18.530 --> 00:07:23.960
I've already spent a third
of my life behind bars.

00:07:23.960 --> 00:07:28.830
In 1996, my life
drastically changed forever.

00:07:28.830 --> 00:07:32.570
I was convicted as a first
time, non-violent drug offender,

00:07:32.570 --> 00:07:36.230
and sentenced to life
in federal prison.

00:07:36.230 --> 00:07:41.120
I'd always thought that only the
most heinous crimes warranted

00:07:41.120 --> 00:07:43.610
a life without parole sentence.

00:07:43.610 --> 00:07:48.500
I have the exact same
sentence as Charles Manson.

00:07:48.500 --> 00:07:51.220
Prior to coming to prison.

00:07:51.220 --> 00:07:55.040
I lived, I guess you could
say, a pretty productive life.

00:07:55.040 --> 00:07:58.730
I never expected anything
like this to happen to me.

00:07:58.730 --> 00:08:03.230
I had worked in various
professional positions.

00:08:03.230 --> 00:08:05.510
I was working at
Federal Express.

00:08:05.510 --> 00:08:09.960
I had been a manager
with FedEx for 10 years.

00:08:09.960 --> 00:08:11.990
I was also a
facilitator who trained

00:08:11.990 --> 00:08:14.660
other people for management.

00:08:14.660 --> 00:08:18.470
When I lost my job at
10 years with Fed Ex,

00:08:18.470 --> 00:08:20.420
I can tell you that
my life literally

00:08:20.420 --> 00:08:22.920
began to spiral out of control.

00:08:22.920 --> 00:08:27.050
I made one of the worst
choices that I've ever

00:08:27.050 --> 00:08:30.620
made in my life,
which I deeply regret.

00:08:30.620 --> 00:08:35.450
I became involved in
a drug conspiracy.

00:08:35.450 --> 00:08:37.580
I had never sold drugs.

00:08:37.580 --> 00:08:39.830
I had never used drugs.

00:08:39.830 --> 00:08:44.360
And I can tell you, I
literally got in over my head.

00:08:44.360 --> 00:08:47.660
But I tell you, I made
some very different choices

00:08:47.660 --> 00:08:49.940
when I came to prison.

00:08:49.940 --> 00:08:52.960
I want to tell you real quickly,
when I was a young girl,

00:08:52.960 --> 00:08:55.490
I had someone ask
me, Alice, what

00:08:55.490 --> 00:08:57.760
do you want to be
when you grow up?

00:08:57.760 --> 00:09:01.140
And I said, I wanted to
be an incredible woman.

00:09:01.140 --> 00:09:04.430
They said, what is
an incredible woman?

00:09:04.430 --> 00:09:07.040
I said, it's a
woman who goes down

00:09:07.040 --> 00:09:09.940
in history, who makes
changes in life,

00:09:09.940 --> 00:09:14.930
who makes their print in life,
and impacts people's lives.

00:09:14.930 --> 00:09:18.240
That's the kind of woman
that I wanted to be.

00:09:18.240 --> 00:09:23.620
I decided when I came to prison,
that because I was in prison,

00:09:23.620 --> 00:09:27.080
prison bars don't have
to contain your dreams.

00:09:27.080 --> 00:09:30.740
I still wanted to be
an incredible woman.

00:09:30.740 --> 00:09:35.060
So I looked around
my new environment

00:09:35.060 --> 00:09:40.520
to see how I could impact the
society in prison for good.

00:09:40.520 --> 00:09:43.450
So I started serving
others and making

00:09:43.450 --> 00:09:45.350
a difference in their lives.

00:09:45.350 --> 00:09:48.170
I picked up my pen
and I started writing

00:09:48.170 --> 00:09:52.220
plays, plays that were the
largest inmate participation

00:09:52.220 --> 00:09:54.440
programs in the prison.

00:09:54.440 --> 00:09:57.980
People who thought they
couldn't do anything,

00:09:57.980 --> 00:10:01.310
they learned how to do
theatrical productions.

00:10:01.310 --> 00:10:02.720
They learned how to act.

00:10:02.720 --> 00:10:05.090
I started choreographing dance.

00:10:05.090 --> 00:10:09.240
I found people that
the gift of artistry

00:10:09.240 --> 00:10:14.540
was stirred up in them, and
beautiful, beautiful backdrops.

00:10:14.540 --> 00:10:19.850
And our plays became
just known everywhere.

00:10:19.850 --> 00:10:23.300
I also started
mentoring women to see

00:10:23.300 --> 00:10:26.970
if I can help be deterred
from a life of crime.

00:10:26.970 --> 00:10:30.170
I used the experience that I
had with interviewing and job

00:10:30.170 --> 00:10:34.980
preparedness to prepare other
women to go outside and be

00:10:34.980 --> 00:10:36.360
productive citizens.

00:10:36.360 --> 00:10:39.950
ANDREA JAMES: And
Miss Alice, I want

00:10:39.950 --> 00:10:41.800
us to have the
opportunity, Miss Alice,

00:10:41.800 --> 00:10:44.570
to talk a little
bit about the fact

00:10:44.570 --> 00:10:50.450
that we don't have
available to us right now,

00:10:50.450 --> 00:10:53.240
The Clemency Project,
we do not have that.

00:10:53.240 --> 00:10:56.090
We have a Justice
Department now that

00:10:56.090 --> 00:11:01.550
wants to turn the clocks
back to a place in time that

00:11:01.550 --> 00:11:04.910
is dark and draconian
and something that,

00:11:04.910 --> 00:11:08.601
with all of the education that
we have learned over the years

00:11:08.601 --> 00:11:10.850
and throughout the Obama
administration about the need

00:11:10.850 --> 00:11:12.340
to decarcerate--

00:11:12.340 --> 00:11:15.350
why, Miss Alice,
you are in a prison,

00:11:15.350 --> 00:11:17.840
one of many federal
women's prisons

00:11:17.840 --> 00:11:21.910
that are full of
women who are there

00:11:21.910 --> 00:11:26.330
and only but for conspiracy
laws in this country that allow

00:11:26.330 --> 00:11:30.170
these women to be thrown in and
charged and held responsible

00:11:30.170 --> 00:11:32.840
for the same amount
as the person who

00:11:32.840 --> 00:11:34.610
is the leader of the drug ring.

00:11:34.610 --> 00:11:38.540
Why Miss Alice, why is it
so incredibly important

00:11:38.540 --> 00:11:42.200
that we continue and raise
awareness in places like this,

00:11:42.200 --> 00:11:44.720
about the need to
push and to continue

00:11:44.720 --> 00:11:49.430
to push for the freedom of women
like yourself through clemency?

00:11:49.430 --> 00:11:52.110
ALICE MARIE JOHNSON:
Well, conspiracy--

00:11:52.110 --> 00:11:55.340
I can say this about conspiracy.

00:11:55.340 --> 00:11:58.520
Many of the women in here
were women who did not

00:11:58.520 --> 00:12:00.920
have those types of roles.

00:12:00.920 --> 00:12:04.220
But they are charged
with leadership roles.

00:12:04.220 --> 00:12:06.800
They have to take on
the responsibility

00:12:06.800 --> 00:12:08.580
of the entire conspiracy.

00:12:08.580 --> 00:12:10.610
Because I was dumb.

00:12:10.610 --> 00:12:13.820
I was [INAUDIBLE] because
I had never been in prison.

00:12:13.820 --> 00:12:16.130
I didn't even know people
who had served time.

00:12:16.130 --> 00:12:19.010
So I didn't know what a
conspiracy charge meant.

00:12:19.010 --> 00:12:21.830
It means that you are
charged with every element

00:12:21.830 --> 00:12:22.990
of the crime.

00:12:22.990 --> 00:12:25.640
You are held responsible
for every act

00:12:25.640 --> 00:12:29.569
that anyone else has committed,
whether you had knowledge

00:12:29.569 --> 00:12:30.860
of what they were doing or not.

00:12:30.860 --> 00:12:32.840
That's why it's
called conspiracy,

00:12:32.840 --> 00:12:36.010
so it becomes a catch
all for everything.

00:12:36.010 --> 00:12:39.450
And these women, most
of them are mothers.

00:12:39.450 --> 00:12:42.170
I'd say 95% of them are mothers.

00:12:42.170 --> 00:12:44.870
And I tell you, we
know that women,

00:12:44.870 --> 00:12:46.410
not to say anything
about the men,

00:12:46.410 --> 00:12:49.490
but the mother is the
nucleus of the family.

00:12:49.490 --> 00:12:53.270
When a mother is taken out
of the home, so many times

00:12:53.270 --> 00:12:56.810
the family is split apart.

00:12:56.810 --> 00:12:58.940
When a man is taken
out of the home,

00:12:58.940 --> 00:13:01.650
the woman will hold it down.

00:13:01.650 --> 00:13:05.820
But when the women, most of the
time, and it's just the truth--

00:13:05.820 --> 00:13:09.540
the children are sent away
to live with relatives,

00:13:09.540 --> 00:13:13.470
foster care, and too many times
they are sent to the streets

00:13:13.470 --> 00:13:14.930
to be raised that the streets.

00:13:14.930 --> 00:13:18.610
And the cycle of
incarceration continues.

00:13:18.610 --> 00:13:24.200
So this cause of women and
girls is saving the families.

00:13:24.200 --> 00:13:28.140
ANDREA JAMES: Now Miss Alice,
