00:21:16.399 --> 00:21:18.440
MALIKA SAADA SAAR: So I
wanted to ask each of you

00:21:18.440 --> 00:21:24.784
to talk in more depth around how
mass incarceration has impacted

00:21:24.784 --> 00:21:25.325
you directly.

00:21:27.450 --> 00:21:29.450
MIYHOSI BENTON: So mass
incarceration-- so like,

00:21:29.450 --> 00:21:31.940
I was arrested at the age of 19.

00:21:31.940 --> 00:21:34.560
I was two months pregnant.

00:21:34.560 --> 00:21:37.290
And I did a total of four
years in three different states

00:21:37.290 --> 00:21:39.990
New York, New Jersey,
and Pennsylvania.

00:21:39.990 --> 00:21:44.370
And while incarcerated, I
gave birth to my daughter

00:21:44.370 --> 00:21:46.260
at the Bethel Hills
Correctional Facility,

00:21:46.260 --> 00:21:50.400
which is the maximum
facility in New York state.

00:21:50.400 --> 00:21:53.130
And I spent many
birthdays behind bars.

00:21:53.130 --> 00:21:55.890
And when you think about
your 21st birthday,

00:21:55.890 --> 00:21:59.180
you really don't think
about celebrating it inside,

00:21:59.180 --> 00:22:02.010
behind the cell, with the
women you barely know.

00:22:02.010 --> 00:22:04.120
But you make the best of it.

00:22:04.120 --> 00:22:08.970
And as women we make the
best of our situations.

00:22:08.970 --> 00:22:12.114
I was also fortunate to be
able to go into the nursery.

00:22:12.114 --> 00:22:13.530
Bethel Hills
Correctional Facility

00:22:13.530 --> 00:22:16.890
has a nursery where they
allow the woman to stay

00:22:16.890 --> 00:22:19.260
with their children
up to a year.

00:22:19.260 --> 00:22:21.340
And I was able to
bond with my daughter.

00:22:21.340 --> 00:22:23.850
And after I sent her
home, they transferred me

00:22:23.850 --> 00:22:28.050
to Albion Correctional Facility,
which is the medium security

00:22:28.050 --> 00:22:31.680
facility in New York state
on the borderline of Canada.

00:22:31.680 --> 00:22:35.177
And from there, I didn't
receive another visit

00:22:35.177 --> 00:22:36.510
from neither one of my children.

00:22:36.510 --> 00:22:39.930
Because I had a son that was one
years old when I went inside.

00:22:39.930 --> 00:22:44.400
And this is not like
a unique situation.

00:22:44.400 --> 00:22:47.940
75 percent of women that
are incarcerated at the time

00:22:47.940 --> 00:22:49.440
are moms.

00:22:49.440 --> 00:22:52.380
And I was one of those
moms that was far away

00:22:52.380 --> 00:22:55.620
and did not have access to
being able to see my children.

00:22:55.620 --> 00:22:57.570
And speaking on a
phone or letters

00:22:57.570 --> 00:22:59.395
don't cut it when you
have young children,

00:22:59.395 --> 00:23:01.020
and they don't cut
it for any children,

00:23:01.020 --> 00:23:03.780
because you're not
afforded the bond that you

00:23:03.780 --> 00:23:07.950
need to nurture and
to bring them up.

00:23:07.950 --> 00:23:10.980
So after my four years,
I came home and reunited

00:23:10.980 --> 00:23:13.440
with my son and my daughter.

00:23:13.440 --> 00:23:20.810
[APPLAUSE]

00:23:20.810 --> 00:23:29.210
TOPEKA SAM: So my impact
with incarceration

00:23:29.210 --> 00:23:34.580
has started just being an
African-American woman.

00:23:34.580 --> 00:23:38.610
Family members and things
that have been incarcerated

00:23:38.610 --> 00:23:39.520
are friends.

00:23:39.520 --> 00:23:45.000
But my family, my parents, they
were entrepreneurs, franchise

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:45.500
owners.

00:23:45.500 --> 00:23:48.800
And they had us
living in the area

00:23:48.800 --> 00:23:50.330
where we were the
only black family.

00:23:50.330 --> 00:23:52.700
And partly, it was to
protect us from what was

00:23:52.700 --> 00:23:53.910
happening within the country.

00:23:53.910 --> 00:23:55.493
And the things that
they went through,

00:23:55.493 --> 00:23:57.050
being from New York City.

00:23:57.050 --> 00:23:59.290
And when I went off
to go to college

00:23:59.290 --> 00:24:03.050
is when I got exposed directly
to different things that

00:24:03.050 --> 00:24:05.030
were really happening
in the world,

00:24:05.030 --> 00:24:07.160
and started making
poor choices and really

00:24:07.160 --> 00:24:11.170
buying into the narrative
of what being black

00:24:11.170 --> 00:24:13.520
looked like in America.

00:24:13.520 --> 00:24:16.730
And that entailed
dating guys who

00:24:16.730 --> 00:24:20.940
may have been drug dealing
and things of that nature.

00:24:20.940 --> 00:24:23.630
And then not even
understanding what

00:24:23.630 --> 00:24:26.810
had happened in this country
to even cause it to happen

00:24:26.810 --> 00:24:28.460
within our communities.

00:24:28.460 --> 00:24:33.710
So I had gotten in trouble, and
I would get arrested, and then

00:24:33.710 --> 00:24:35.180
go on probation.

00:24:35.180 --> 00:24:36.540
And it was a cycle.

00:24:36.540 --> 00:24:42.440
Yet still in college and
still maintaining employment

00:24:42.440 --> 00:24:45.320
and building a career
or starting a business.

00:24:45.320 --> 00:24:48.590
And so when I was incarcerated
in federal prison,

00:24:48.590 --> 00:24:51.270
I was incarcerated
for 3 and 1/2 years.

00:24:51.270 --> 00:24:53.300
And part of what Miss
Alice spoke about,

00:24:53.300 --> 00:24:54.800
and what Miyhosi
just touched on,

00:24:54.800 --> 00:24:59.360
was the fact that I had met so
many women who had children.

00:24:59.360 --> 00:25:02.120
And so many women in
the federal prison--

00:25:02.120 --> 00:25:05.060
we are taken far, far away.

00:25:05.060 --> 00:25:07.430
In the Northeast,
Danbury, Connecticut

00:25:07.430 --> 00:25:09.680
was the only women's
federal prison.

00:25:09.680 --> 00:25:12.380
And I was camp designated,
so I was in Danbury.

00:25:12.380 --> 00:25:15.150
And you had women from all
up and down the East Coast

00:25:15.150 --> 00:25:16.950
and Midwest who were there.

00:25:16.950 --> 00:25:19.430
Yet I would be in
the visiting room,

00:25:19.430 --> 00:25:21.830
and there would be no one there.

00:25:21.830 --> 00:25:24.540
And partly, it's because
you had the parents, who

00:25:24.540 --> 00:25:27.320
were home, who are elderly on
fixed incomes, who were taking

00:25:27.320 --> 00:25:31.580
care of the children and
had to choose whether or not

00:25:31.580 --> 00:25:35.000
they could have the children
go to see their parents

00:25:35.000 --> 00:25:38.210
or feed the children and
make sure that they were OK.

00:25:38.210 --> 00:25:41.330
And in then meeting women
who had had already done

00:25:41.330 --> 00:25:45.170
20 years in prison,
I knew at that point

00:25:45.170 --> 00:25:48.350
that it was my
responsibility to then take

00:25:48.350 --> 00:25:51.440
what it was that I learned, even
being impacted by a conspiracy

00:25:51.440 --> 00:25:55.500
charge, and by the grace of God,
I did not get life in prison.

00:25:55.500 --> 00:25:57.800
But those conspiracy
laws are just that.

00:25:57.800 --> 00:26:00.200
I had no drugs in
my case at all.

00:26:00.200 --> 00:26:04.950
Yet I was charged with
having 80 kilos of cocaine.

00:26:04.950 --> 00:26:08.840
So when you look at
just how that law is

00:26:08.840 --> 00:26:11.600
and what is in place and what
it does to our communities,

00:26:11.600 --> 00:26:15.020
specifically women and girls.

00:26:15.020 --> 00:26:16.910
One of the policies in
the reform that we're

00:26:16.910 --> 00:26:21.330
doing at the National Council is
to change that conspiracy law.

00:26:21.330 --> 00:26:26.030
So now as a national organizer,
we go around the country.

00:26:26.030 --> 00:26:29.900
We are mobilizing, hoping to
get 100,000 members, which

00:26:29.900 --> 00:26:32.570
includes formerly incarcerated
and incarcerated women,

00:26:32.570 --> 00:26:35.870
directly impacted children
of incarcerated parents,

00:26:35.870 --> 00:26:40.220
and people like you who are
movement family and allies who

00:26:40.220 --> 00:26:43.010
can help us in moving this work
and getting the message out

00:26:43.010 --> 00:26:45.020
so that we can end the
incarceration of women

00:26:45.020 --> 00:26:45.759
and girls.

00:26:45.759 --> 00:26:47.300
MALIKA SAADA SAAR:
So, Topeka, I want

00:26:47.300 --> 00:26:49.280
to just surface
more of what you're

00:26:49.280 --> 00:26:51.410
talking about with the
conspiracy charges.

00:26:51.410 --> 00:26:54.200
Because we know,
right, that most women

00:26:54.200 --> 00:26:56.630
who are behind bars
at federal and state

00:26:56.630 --> 00:27:00.110
correctional facilities
are mothers to children

00:27:00.110 --> 00:27:01.670
under the age of 18.

00:27:01.670 --> 00:27:05.540
We know that most women
and mothers behind bars

00:27:05.540 --> 00:27:09.710
are first time,
nonviolent felons.

00:27:09.710 --> 00:27:12.950
What is going on with
the conspiracy charges--

00:27:12.950 --> 00:27:16.190
that first time
nonviolent felons,

00:27:16.190 --> 00:27:19.880
who are mothers to children
under the age of 18,

00:27:19.880 --> 00:27:24.260
are being put behind bars for
20 years or a lifetime sentence?

00:27:24.260 --> 00:27:26.150
Can you explain that more to us?

00:27:26.150 --> 00:27:27.110
TOPEKA SAM: Absolutely.

00:27:27.110 --> 00:27:33.260
It's happening because
it's a retaliation tactic.

00:27:33.260 --> 00:27:36.590
It's used because, if
you don't cooperate

00:27:36.590 --> 00:27:38.660
in whatever the charges
are-- and a lot of times

00:27:38.660 --> 00:27:41.370
the women really have
no idea what's going on.

00:27:41.370 --> 00:27:43.100
I mean think about you.

00:27:43.100 --> 00:27:45.560
Do you really know what your
boyfriend or your husband

00:27:45.560 --> 00:27:47.260
is doing when they leave you?

00:27:47.260 --> 00:27:48.350
You don't.

00:27:48.350 --> 00:27:52.610
And so they want you to then
speak on information that you

00:27:52.610 --> 00:27:55.010
don't-- make up information,
it's people that you may not

00:27:55.010 --> 00:27:57.170
have even met in the conspiracy.

00:27:57.170 --> 00:27:59.930
Yet, if you don't
cooperate, you end up

00:27:59.930 --> 00:28:03.130
getting hit with-- as Miss
Alice described-- everything

00:28:03.130 --> 00:28:05.420
that's in that charge.

00:28:05.420 --> 00:28:07.400
And then you ending
up in life in prison

00:28:07.400 --> 00:28:10.890
because of the sentencing
guidelines and the guidelines

00:28:10.890 --> 00:28:11.390
chart.

00:28:11.390 --> 00:28:14.180
And the fact that
you are charged

00:28:14.180 --> 00:28:18.080
based on the amount of
drugs that is said to have--

00:28:18.080 --> 00:28:19.850
not actually have.

00:28:19.850 --> 00:28:22.130
So they call it ghost dope.

00:28:22.130 --> 00:28:26.240
You don't even have to find it,
yet you'll be charged with it.

00:28:26.240 --> 00:28:28.610
And that's how the system
is being manipulated

00:28:28.610 --> 00:28:31.520
and so many women and girls
are being caught and swept

00:28:31.520 --> 00:28:33.110
into the conspiracy.

00:28:33.110 --> 00:28:37.780
And yet it's really a conspiracy
against our women and girls.

00:28:37.780 --> 00:28:41.150
MALIKA SAADA SAAR: Do you
want to add to that, Miyhosi?

00:28:41.150 --> 00:28:42.260
MIYHOSI BENTON: Um, no.

00:28:42.260 --> 00:28:44.760
MALIKA SAADA SAAR: I'm going
to ask you a different question

00:28:44.760 --> 00:28:47.300
to add to, but but I just
want to make sure that people

00:28:47.300 --> 00:28:48.530
understand what you've said.

00:28:48.530 --> 00:28:50.750
Because this is really
one of the key ways

00:28:50.750 --> 00:28:53.120
that when we talk
about the war on drugs

00:28:53.120 --> 00:28:56.210
and the over prosecution of
black and brown communities

00:28:56.210 --> 00:28:58.700
and the overcriminalization
that has happened,

00:28:58.700 --> 00:29:02.120
these conspiracy
charges are at the heart

00:29:02.120 --> 00:29:06.800
of how we talk about the war
on drugs' devastating impact

00:29:06.800 --> 00:29:08.060
on our communities.

00:29:08.060 --> 00:29:10.460
But often what doesn't
get talked about

00:29:10.460 --> 00:29:13.640
is the particular ways
that it's played out

00:29:13.640 --> 00:29:16.100
in the lives of women.

00:29:16.100 --> 00:29:18.620
So Miyhosi, I wanted
to talk to you

00:29:18.620 --> 00:29:22.820
about this issue of conditions
of confinement for our women

00:29:22.820 --> 00:29:24.370
and mothers.

00:29:24.370 --> 00:29:30.320
When I was heading up an NGO
on gender-based violence,

00:29:30.320 --> 00:29:33.560
some women who were
previously incarcerated

00:29:33.560 --> 00:29:37.460
talked to me about how
they had been, during labor

00:29:37.460 --> 00:29:39.340
and childbirth, shackled.

00:29:39.340 --> 00:29:41.330
And I thought they
were explaining to me

00:29:41.330 --> 00:29:45.500
like some crazy thing that
was an aberrant violation

00:29:45.500 --> 00:29:49.010
of practice and policy
at a southern prison,

00:29:49.010 --> 00:29:52.100
because they were
coming from Tennessee.

00:29:52.100 --> 00:29:56.210
And I started to find out
that actually shackling women

00:29:56.210 --> 00:29:59.750
during labor and childbirth
is standard procedure.

00:29:59.750 --> 00:30:02.570
It was standard procedure in
all of our federal correctional

00:30:02.570 --> 00:30:03.590
facilities.

00:30:03.590 --> 00:30:06.350
Fortunately, we were
able to change that.

00:30:06.350 --> 00:30:11.810
It remains standard procedure
in most of our state prisons.

00:30:11.810 --> 00:30:14.480
So let me be clear
in what I am saying.

00:30:14.480 --> 00:30:18.050
When a woman behind
bars who is pregnant

00:30:18.050 --> 00:30:22.880
is in labor and childbirth,
she is shackled.

00:30:22.880 --> 00:30:26.000
She's shackled by
her arms, her legs.

00:30:26.000 --> 00:30:29.630
I heard one case of a
belly shackle during labor.

00:30:29.630 --> 00:30:31.790
Can you talk to us
more about this policy

00:30:31.790 --> 00:30:35.630
and the incredible work that
you've done to change it?

00:30:35.630 --> 00:30:38.790
MIYHOSI BENTON: So I
was one of those women.

00:30:38.790 --> 00:30:40.200
I was illegally shackled.

00:30:40.200 --> 00:30:44.190
In New York state, we
had a law, a 2009 law

00:30:44.190 --> 00:30:48.090
that banned the barbaric
shackle in a pregnant women.

00:30:48.090 --> 00:30:50.910
When I went in 2009,
I was pregnant.

00:30:50.910 --> 00:30:53.820
I gave birth to my
daughter in 2010.

00:30:53.820 --> 00:30:57.270
And when you're inside,
you don't know your rights.

00:30:57.270 --> 00:30:59.670
And that's one of the
ways they control you.

00:30:59.670 --> 00:31:02.490
By not allowing you
to educate yourself

00:31:02.490 --> 00:31:05.430
or to educate you on
what your rights are.

00:31:05.430 --> 00:31:08.110
So the less you know,
the best for them.

00:31:08.110 --> 00:31:11.280
So I didn't know that it was
illegal to shackle me while I

00:31:11.280 --> 00:31:13.620
was in labor or delivering.

00:31:13.620 --> 00:31:16.830
And my experience, where I was--

00:31:16.830 --> 00:31:21.260
so just imagine, for me, like
for anyone, giving birth--

00:31:21.260 --> 00:31:23.550
like a joyous moment,
a moment that you're

00:31:23.550 --> 00:31:26.140
supposed to be with your
loved ones, your family,

00:31:26.140 --> 00:31:29.340
sharing and welcoming
a new life--

00:31:29.340 --> 00:31:32.640
and that moment being
distorted and corrupted

00:31:32.640 --> 00:31:37.020
by a correctional
officer who doesn't

00:31:37.020 --> 00:31:39.390
have any good
intentions towards you.

00:31:39.390 --> 00:31:41.760
It's malicious energy.

00:31:41.760 --> 00:31:44.610
And for me, while
I was giving birth,

00:31:44.610 --> 00:31:47.340
I had the correction officer
standing between my legs

00:31:47.340 --> 00:31:50.610
while pushing, while
the doctor was pushing.

00:31:50.610 --> 00:31:53.920
And you know, you
want to say something.

00:31:53.920 --> 00:31:56.220
And you want to like,
try to understand

00:31:56.220 --> 00:31:59.580
how can someone in their
right mind think it's OK.

00:31:59.580 --> 00:32:01.560
Like, how is this
humanly possible

00:32:01.560 --> 00:32:03.930
that anyone in the world
would think it's OK for you

00:32:03.930 --> 00:32:07.800
to stand where I'm trying
to deliver my baby?

00:32:07.800 --> 00:32:09.465
And not only put
my life at risk,

00:32:09.465 --> 00:32:11.470
but my child's life at risk?

00:32:11.470 --> 00:32:14.580
So you not only strip me
of my dignity, my respect,

00:32:14.580 --> 00:32:17.700
my self-worth, but you going
to put my life in danger

00:32:17.700 --> 00:32:19.630
and my child's life in danger?

00:32:19.630 --> 00:32:22.230
So for me that was
a really hard part.

00:32:22.230 --> 00:32:25.410
And then the correctional
officer and the doctor

00:32:25.410 --> 00:32:28.350
was arguing, because the
doctor did understand

00:32:28.350 --> 00:32:30.450
like, this is my job.

00:32:30.450 --> 00:32:32.490
This was her job
to deliver the baby

00:32:32.490 --> 00:32:34.330
and make sure the mom
and the baby was OK.

00:32:34.330 --> 00:32:35.955
And she couldn't do
her job to the best

00:32:35.955 --> 00:32:39.080
of her abilities because
of the correction officer.

00:32:39.080 --> 00:32:43.710
But after I gave birth,
they automatically

00:32:43.710 --> 00:32:45.600
handcuff you right away.

00:32:45.600 --> 00:32:48.090
Like, you don't really
even have a moment to bond

00:32:48.090 --> 00:32:50.130
with your child,
not to feed them,

00:32:50.130 --> 00:32:53.170
not to just hold them and
take in that precious moment.

00:32:53.170 --> 00:32:58.091
And when you give
birth, they send you

00:32:58.091 --> 00:32:59.340
to Westchester Medical Center.

00:32:59.340 --> 00:33:02.910
So you are in a prison ward
inside a Westchester Medical

00:33:02.910 --> 00:33:03.616
Center.

00:33:03.616 --> 00:33:06.240
And then they bring you in, they
shackle and they handcuff you.

00:33:06.240 --> 00:33:08.490
And they may allow you
to see your child maybe

00:33:08.490 --> 00:33:10.660
once or twice, if you're lucky.

00:33:10.660 --> 00:33:12.720
But in that process, once
again you're shackled

00:33:12.720 --> 00:33:14.700
and you're handcuffed,
and it's the metal

00:33:14.700 --> 00:33:17.010
chain around your waist,
and it's the handcuffs,

00:33:17.010 --> 00:33:18.410
and it's the ankle shackles.

00:33:18.410 --> 00:33:20.910
And then you're brought into a
wheelchair to see your child.

00:33:20.910 --> 00:33:24.600
And they remove
just the handcuffs.

00:33:24.600 --> 00:33:26.860
So you literally cannot
walk with your child.

00:33:26.860 --> 00:33:28.860
And all of these things
are illegal at the time,

00:33:28.860 --> 00:33:31.170
and no one is held
accountable for these things.

00:33:31.170 --> 00:33:34.920
So it is OK for us to be put
into the criminal justice

00:33:34.920 --> 00:33:36.510
system for breaking the law.

00:33:36.510 --> 00:33:39.630
But it's OK for the
Department of Corrections

00:33:39.630 --> 00:33:41.640
to break it day in and day out.

00:33:41.640 --> 00:33:42.180
Why?

00:33:42.180 --> 00:33:44.430
Because they do not
value our lives.

00:33:44.430 --> 00:33:48.330
Black girls, women-- our
lives are not valued--

00:33:48.330 --> 00:33:51.840
not in society, not in the
current administrative system

00:33:51.840 --> 00:33:54.060
that we have right now,
not inside a prison.

00:33:54.060 --> 00:33:55.320
Our lives are not valued.

00:33:55.320 --> 00:33:58.340
And it was just
another reminder.

00:33:58.340 --> 00:34:02.820
So after I went through
that whole process

00:34:02.820 --> 00:34:06.390
of being traumatized and
humiliated and just--

00:34:06.390 --> 00:34:09.780
I thought, like, when I come
home, I have to speak up.

00:34:09.780 --> 00:34:11.699
Because if we don't
speak up, the ones who

00:34:11.699 --> 00:34:15.000
are being criminalized, the
ones who are being dehumanized,

00:34:15.000 --> 00:34:17.580
if we don't speak
up, then who will?

00:34:17.580 --> 00:34:19.080
It's our stories.

00:34:19.080 --> 00:34:20.880
We're the ones who
are experiencing

00:34:20.880 --> 00:34:24.480
these horrific
injustices all the time.

00:34:24.480 --> 00:34:29.130
So I came home, and I met
with [INAUDIBLE] Tamar,

00:34:29.130 --> 00:34:31.770
who was at the correctional
association at the time.

00:34:31.770 --> 00:34:34.320
And they came up to me
and was, like, well,

00:34:34.320 --> 00:34:35.940
were you illegally shackled?

00:34:35.940 --> 00:34:37.260
And I was like, I was.

00:34:37.260 --> 00:34:40.116
Like, I was so excited
that there was something--

00:34:40.116 --> 00:34:41.699
and there was
organizations and people

00:34:41.699 --> 00:34:44.370
out there that cared
and were fighting it.

00:34:44.370 --> 00:34:45.330
So I got involved.

00:34:45.330 --> 00:34:49.230
And what we did, we spoke
to legislators at Albany.

00:34:49.230 --> 00:34:50.159
We had letters.

00:34:50.159 --> 00:34:53.250
We dealt with the media.

00:34:53.250 --> 00:34:56.340
We did interviews,
and we rallied outside

00:34:56.340 --> 00:34:58.200
of the governor's office.

00:34:58.200 --> 00:34:59.280
We fought and fought.

00:34:59.280 --> 00:35:01.440
We made films about
the experience

00:35:01.440 --> 00:35:03.780
of what we had to go through.

00:35:03.780 --> 00:35:07.470
And we was able to have
this progressive law pass.

00:35:07.470 --> 00:35:11.880
So it reinforced the 2009 law.

00:35:11.880 --> 00:35:16.290
And it also expanded it so your
whole pregnancy you were not

00:35:16.290 --> 00:35:19.500
allowed to be shackled
and handcuffed at all.

00:35:19.500 --> 00:35:22.950
And you had the
privacy of not having

00:35:22.950 --> 00:35:25.920
to worry about a correctional
officer being inside

00:35:25.920 --> 00:35:28.710
your room while giving birth.

00:35:28.710 --> 00:35:29.970
It expanded so much.

00:35:29.970 --> 00:35:32.880
[APPLAUSE]

00:35:32.880 --> 00:35:34.980
And New York state
now has the most

00:35:34.980 --> 00:35:38.140
progressive anti-shackling
law in the country.

00:35:38.140 --> 00:35:42.330
And it's because a woman
directly impacted speaking up

00:35:42.330 --> 00:35:44.509
in collaboration with allies.

00:35:44.509 --> 00:35:46.050
And that would not
have been possible

00:35:46.050 --> 00:35:50.040
if it was not for the chances
that we had to speak our piece

00:35:50.040 --> 00:35:51.450
and to make it right.

00:35:51.450 --> 00:35:54.000
And we have to continue to
do this for any injustice

00:35:54.000 --> 00:35:55.710
that we witnessed
or that we bear.

00:35:55.710 --> 00:36:00.720
[APPLAUSE]

00:36:00.720 --> 00:36:02.700
MALIKA SAADA SAAR:
Thank you for your work.

00:36:02.700 --> 00:36:06.160
Topeka, we are at
this incredible moment

00:36:06.160 --> 00:36:11.980
around how, finally, it's
a bipartisan conversation

00:36:11.980 --> 00:36:14.290
on ending mass incarceration.

00:36:14.290 --> 00:36:17.450
Finally, we have
Republicans and Democrats,

00:36:17.450 --> 00:36:22.000
and in the public square,
talking about the war on drugs

00:36:22.000 --> 00:36:24.940
was an egregious
violation of human rights.

00:36:24.940 --> 00:36:29.950
Finally, we are saying that
mass incarceration must end.

00:36:29.950 --> 00:36:33.940
But the women who
have been locked up,

00:36:33.940 --> 00:36:37.150
who are still behind
bars, like Miss Alice,

00:36:37.150 --> 00:36:40.570
are not part of
these conversations.

00:36:40.570 --> 00:36:44.260
What needs to happen
in order to make sure

00:36:44.260 --> 00:36:47.740
that at this critical
moment of reform

00:36:47.740 --> 00:36:50.650
the women are not left behind?

00:36:50.650 --> 00:36:53.860
TOPEKA SAM: Well, what needs to
happen is what's happening now.

00:36:53.860 --> 00:36:56.590
Women like you, who are
in these spaces, who

00:36:56.590 --> 00:37:00.580
are making it necessary, and
are committing to this work

00:37:00.580 --> 00:37:04.090
to allow us, those who have
been directly impacted,

00:37:04.090 --> 00:37:06.430
to have our seat at the table.

00:37:06.430 --> 00:37:10.300
Our mantra at the council is
nothing about us without us.

00:37:10.300 --> 00:37:12.590
And so that's because, as
Andrea had said earlier,

00:37:12.590 --> 00:37:14.080
we are the experts.

00:37:14.080 --> 00:37:16.240
And how do you know
what we need if you

00:37:16.240 --> 00:37:19.240
don't ask us and
engage us in changing

00:37:19.240 --> 00:37:21.040
these laws and these policies?

00:37:21.040 --> 00:37:24.700
And as Miss Alice said, I
just want to reinforce that,

00:37:24.700 --> 00:37:26.800
if not you, then who?

00:37:26.800 --> 00:37:29.380
You can't look to your neighbor
or look to someone else

00:37:29.380 --> 00:37:32.320
and say that it's
their responsibility.

00:37:32.320 --> 00:37:36.490
As humans in this world,
it is our responsibility

00:37:36.490 --> 00:37:38.530
and commitment to
one another in order

00:37:38.530 --> 00:37:41.050
to make sure that
we are shifting this

00:37:41.050 --> 00:37:45.610
to this disgusting
criminal justice system

00:37:45.610 --> 00:37:50.074
into a more human
justice system.

00:37:50.074 --> 00:37:52.230
MALIKA SAADA SAAR:
Miyhosi, I want to ask you,

00:37:52.230 --> 00:37:54.850
as we get ready to
end this panel, what

00:37:54.850 --> 00:37:58.600
needs to happen to make
sure that the stories,

00:37:58.600 --> 00:38:02.200
the lived experience,
and expertise of women

00:38:02.200 --> 00:38:05.627
is part of our conversation
on racial justice?

00:38:05.627 --> 00:38:07.210
MIYHOSI BENTON: I
think before we even

00:38:07.210 --> 00:38:08.584
say what needs to
be happening, I

00:38:08.584 --> 00:38:10.480
think we need to
recognize and acknowledge

00:38:10.480 --> 00:38:12.550
what has been happening.

00:38:12.550 --> 00:38:16.300
So women on the inside always
played leadership roles.

00:38:16.300 --> 00:38:18.370
They made change when
change was needed.

00:38:18.370 --> 00:38:21.280
In New York state, I can
speak for New York state,

00:38:21.280 --> 00:38:24.730
in New York state, women
brought college back.

00:38:24.730 --> 00:38:27.850
They had the first
HIV education program,

00:38:27.850 --> 00:38:30.380
which was modeled across
the whole country.

00:38:30.380 --> 00:38:33.456
They also had the children
center and parenting centers.

00:38:33.456 --> 00:38:35.080
These are the kind
of things that women

00:38:35.080 --> 00:38:36.910
did before coming out.

00:38:36.910 --> 00:38:39.550
And then now, they're out,
and they still fighting.

00:38:39.550 --> 00:38:41.620
So I feel like we
just need to keep

00:38:41.620 --> 00:38:45.040
in mind these are the women we
need to have at the forefront.

00:38:45.040 --> 00:38:48.017
These are the women that had the
experience and the expertise.

00:38:48.017 --> 00:38:49.600
And these are the
women that are going

00:38:49.600 --> 00:38:51.790
to be change agents
to shift away

