car, it ceased to exist.

00:44:01.290 --> 00:44:03.420
All of our holidays,
whether it's

00:44:03.420 --> 00:44:06.390
Christmas or
birthdays or anything,

00:44:06.390 --> 00:44:09.090
we had to go through
it in a visiting room.

00:44:09.090 --> 00:44:13.500
Or we never had that
physical relationship,

00:44:13.500 --> 00:44:16.050
that caring and nurturing.

00:44:16.050 --> 00:44:18.570
That there's just that
availability for both of us

00:44:18.570 --> 00:44:22.110
to sit down and be able
to communicate thoroughly

00:44:22.110 --> 00:44:23.610
and adequately.

00:44:23.610 --> 00:44:26.220
And I think that's
most effective when

00:44:26.220 --> 00:44:30.452
it comes to that actual
stable relationship

00:44:30.452 --> 00:44:31.410
between the two of you.

00:44:31.410 --> 00:44:34.710
Because no matter how much
you talk on the phone--

00:44:34.710 --> 00:44:38.940
where you have 15 minute
phone calls that cost $3,

00:44:38.940 --> 00:44:41.310
and you have 300
minutes a month.

00:44:41.310 --> 00:44:43.350
The way that my father's
visitation is set up

00:44:43.350 --> 00:44:45.550
is he can only get
five visits a month.

00:44:45.550 --> 00:44:48.870
And out of 365 days, that's
just 60 visits a year.

00:44:48.870 --> 00:44:52.450
So not only are we
just restricted,

00:44:52.450 --> 00:44:55.020
it's like we can never
have a relationship

00:44:55.020 --> 00:44:57.120
with real sentimental value.

00:44:57.120 --> 00:44:59.040
Because once my
parents come home,

00:44:59.040 --> 00:45:01.140
they don't truly know who I am.

00:45:01.140 --> 00:45:04.440
And we have to sit,
and I guess, take that,

00:45:04.440 --> 00:45:06.990
and try to build off of it.

00:45:06.990 --> 00:45:09.570
And my mother has
a release date now.

00:45:09.570 --> 00:45:11.852
So it's 2022.

00:45:11.852 --> 00:45:13.560
So it's about five or
six years from now.

00:45:13.560 --> 00:45:17.580
But when she comes home, I'll be
freshly graduated from college.

00:45:17.580 --> 00:45:20.160
And it will be the both
of us sitting in the room

00:45:20.160 --> 00:45:23.520
while I'm an adult, and I'm
a grown woman at this point.

00:45:23.520 --> 00:45:25.187
And she's older.

00:45:25.187 --> 00:45:27.270
And we're trying to place
ourselves in a situation

00:45:27.270 --> 00:45:30.840
where we're getting to know
who each other really truly is.

00:45:30.840 --> 00:45:33.210
And it's kind of devastating
for the both of us.

00:45:33.210 --> 00:45:37.470
And it's practically traumatic,
because we don't know anything.

00:45:37.470 --> 00:45:42.270
And the things that she should
know from me being two or three

00:45:42.270 --> 00:45:44.550
and watching me grow
and watching what I like

00:45:44.550 --> 00:45:47.047
and what I love, that's absent.

00:45:47.047 --> 00:45:48.630
And I don't know
what she truly likes.

00:45:48.630 --> 00:45:52.020
Because it's not the
same as if you're

00:45:52.020 --> 00:45:53.520
riding in a car
with your parent.

00:45:53.520 --> 00:45:56.070
And you sit down,
and you hear a song,

00:45:56.070 --> 00:45:57.540
and you say, oh, I like this.

00:45:57.540 --> 00:45:59.490
And she says, she likes it, too.

00:45:59.490 --> 00:46:02.730
And then we can actually
vibe and enjoy it together,

00:46:02.730 --> 00:46:05.220
versus being on the telephone,
and I say, oh, I like this,

00:46:05.220 --> 00:46:06.510
and she agrees.

00:46:06.510 --> 00:46:08.239
And it's just not the same.

00:46:08.239 --> 00:46:09.780
ANA KASPARIAN: I
think a lot of times

00:46:09.780 --> 00:46:12.630
when we hear about
incarceration and how

00:46:12.630 --> 00:46:15.840
we need to reform our
criminal justice system--

00:46:15.840 --> 00:46:17.400
and it's always
funny to me that it's

00:46:17.400 --> 00:46:19.983
called the justice system, when
there's such a lack of justice

00:46:19.983 --> 00:46:23.160
involved-- we don't really
think about the impact it

00:46:23.160 --> 00:46:26.682
has on the family members of the
person who gets incarcerated.

00:46:26.682 --> 00:46:28.890
Of course, it's a mass
injustice for the person who's

00:46:28.890 --> 00:46:30.270
incarcerated, but
also the family

00:46:30.270 --> 00:46:33.630
members who are torn from their
mothers and their fathers.

00:46:33.630 --> 00:46:38.030
And so I came across an event
that you actually spoke at,

00:46:38.030 --> 00:46:39.840
where you talked
about the first time

00:46:39.840 --> 00:46:42.960
that you had physical
contact with your mother.

00:46:42.960 --> 00:46:44.704
And I thought that
it was so incredible.

00:46:44.704 --> 00:46:46.620
And it shared a perspective
that I don't think

00:46:46.620 --> 00:46:47.884
most people really know about.

00:46:47.884 --> 00:46:49.550
So can you talk about
that a little bit?

00:46:49.550 --> 00:46:52.332
KENDIA RILEY: So
I was speaking on,

00:46:52.332 --> 00:46:53.790
I can't remember
what event it was,

00:46:53.790 --> 00:46:58.180
but my grandmother,
when I was younger,

00:46:58.180 --> 00:47:00.420
she used to take me to
all the different places.

00:47:00.420 --> 00:47:03.330
And my mother was first
in Danbury, Connecticut,

00:47:03.330 --> 00:47:05.050
and we were living in Virginia.

00:47:05.050 --> 00:47:06.750
So that was also
not even the hike.

00:47:06.750 --> 00:47:09.540
We had a fixed income, as
Topeka spoke of earlier.

00:47:09.540 --> 00:47:12.180
So it was hard to travel,
hard to actually get

00:47:12.180 --> 00:47:13.890
that money to go there.

00:47:13.890 --> 00:47:18.000
So Mother's Days we would
go when I was younger.

00:47:18.000 --> 00:47:20.890
But when I became older, it
became a lot more difficult.

00:47:20.890 --> 00:47:22.980
We had a lot more
responsibilities.

00:47:22.980 --> 00:47:25.920
And I didn't realize--

00:47:25.920 --> 00:47:28.080
and it was over this
past summer that I

00:47:28.080 --> 00:47:29.382
went to go visit her in June.

00:47:29.382 --> 00:47:30.840
And I hadn't realized
that I hadn't

00:47:30.840 --> 00:47:32.740
seen my mother for 10 years.

00:47:32.740 --> 00:47:35.850
And when I went to go
visit her, the only thing

00:47:35.850 --> 00:47:37.950
I could remember was
the smell of her hair

00:47:37.950 --> 00:47:40.920
and just sitting in the
visiting room seeing

00:47:40.920 --> 00:47:42.900
how happy and excited
she was to see me

00:47:42.900 --> 00:47:46.500
and then watching everything
just unfold, from the fact

00:47:46.500 --> 00:47:48.890
that the last time she
had actually seen me I

00:47:48.890 --> 00:47:50.790
was eight or nine years old.

00:47:50.790 --> 00:47:51.740
And I was little.

00:47:51.740 --> 00:47:53.220
I was innocent.

00:47:53.220 --> 00:47:56.210
I hadn't been through all the
traumatic events and turmoil

00:47:56.210 --> 00:48:00.030
that I had endured
at that point.

00:48:00.030 --> 00:48:03.080
So looking at her was like
looking at a complete stranger.

00:48:03.080 --> 00:48:06.200
And I couldn't remember
how she looked.

00:48:06.200 --> 00:48:09.680
And just looking
at her, and telling

00:48:09.680 --> 00:48:12.080
my aunt, who visited
with me, and just saying,

00:48:12.080 --> 00:48:13.940
wow, we really do look alike.

00:48:13.940 --> 00:48:16.880
And just kind of looking
into her eyes and thinking,

00:48:16.880 --> 00:48:20.140
I've never seen you
past a photograph.

00:48:20.140 --> 00:48:24.954
Or I've never heard your voice
constantly in front of me,

00:48:24.954 --> 00:48:26.870
like actually going
through my ears other than

00:48:26.870 --> 00:48:28.970
through like the
static of a telephone.

00:48:28.970 --> 00:48:32.660
And I think sitting there and
smelling her and just taking me

00:48:32.660 --> 00:48:34.460
back to the innocence
of my childhood

00:48:34.460 --> 00:48:36.800
and just remembering
that I'm in this, that I

00:48:36.800 --> 00:48:40.220
was in the same exact
predicament as I was then.

00:48:40.220 --> 00:48:43.940
ANA KASPARIAN: How
has your experience

00:48:43.940 --> 00:48:47.940
with having an incarcerated
mother impacted your future?

00:48:47.940 --> 00:48:51.590
Because in every sense of the
word, you are a success story.

00:48:51.590 --> 00:48:54.770
You have a successful
academic career,

00:48:54.770 --> 00:48:56.870
and you've persevered
through what

00:48:56.870 --> 00:48:59.630
most people would stereotype
as something that's impossible,

00:48:59.630 --> 00:49:00.170
right?

00:49:00.170 --> 00:49:02.655
So can you talk to me a
little bit about that.

00:49:02.655 --> 00:49:05.030
KENDIA RILEY: So I feel as
though, with the incarceration

00:49:05.030 --> 00:49:07.010
of both of my
parents, it's embedded

00:49:07.010 --> 00:49:09.770
like a sense of determination
within me, that's kind of--

00:49:09.770 --> 00:49:12.860
I feel if they hadn't
been incarcerated,

00:49:12.860 --> 00:49:15.660
it wouldn't be as stable
in there as it is.

00:49:15.660 --> 00:49:20.060
Because when I was younger,
when I was in elementary school,

00:49:20.060 --> 00:49:22.460
they said that I had
behavioral issues.

00:49:22.460 --> 00:49:23.770
And it was maybe--

00:49:23.770 --> 00:49:25.520
I was in multi-age,
which is a combination

00:49:25.520 --> 00:49:29.130
of first and second
grade, and I would act up.

00:49:29.130 --> 00:49:30.690
I would threaten my teachers.

00:49:30.690 --> 00:49:32.690
I would do all of the above.

00:49:32.690 --> 00:49:36.530
And one day, I wrote a letter
to my teacher threatening her,

00:49:36.530 --> 00:49:39.200
and they had to get a police
officer to come into the room.

00:49:39.200 --> 00:49:42.980
And he had to tell me that
threatening was a felony

00:49:42.980 --> 00:49:45.730
and that basically it
was just irrefutable,

00:49:45.730 --> 00:49:47.750
you can't do that type of thing.

00:49:47.750 --> 00:49:51.230
And my dean stopped and
said, you're so smart.

00:49:51.230 --> 00:49:52.550
I don't understand why.

00:49:52.550 --> 00:49:53.510
Why are you doing it?

00:49:53.510 --> 00:49:55.490
And I told him that I
wanted to go with my parents

00:49:55.490 --> 00:49:56.448
and be with my parents.

00:49:56.448 --> 00:49:59.270
And I thought getting in trouble
would place me in a situation

00:49:59.270 --> 00:50:01.240
where I go to prison
with the both of them.

00:50:01.240 --> 00:50:02.990
And then he explained
that it would either

00:50:02.990 --> 00:50:04.700
get me in juvenile
detention or I'd

00:50:04.700 --> 00:50:07.060
have to go to Merrimack,
which was the main institution

00:50:07.060 --> 00:50:07.670
in Virginia.

00:50:07.670 --> 00:50:11.210
And it was like
that day forward,

00:50:11.210 --> 00:50:14.780
I knew that it was
physically impossible for me

00:50:14.780 --> 00:50:16.310
to be with them at all times.

00:50:16.310 --> 00:50:19.460
And it just set a standard
for me and an expectation

00:50:19.460 --> 00:50:24.320
that, I naturally had
the ability to do well,

00:50:24.320 --> 00:50:26.750
so why not just do well
for the sake of them,

00:50:26.750 --> 00:50:28.550
or for the sake of myself?

00:50:28.550 --> 00:50:31.550
Because if I-- and like, just
the way the police officer

00:50:31.550 --> 00:50:32.600
explained it.

00:50:32.600 --> 00:50:34.970
And just saying how
it's not the same.

00:50:34.970 --> 00:50:37.200
I'm not going to be in
a facility with them,

00:50:37.200 --> 00:50:39.590
and it's not what
I think it to be.

00:50:39.590 --> 00:50:41.270
And just thinking
of, oh, I don't

00:50:41.270 --> 00:50:44.590
want to end up in that
situation at all or ultimately.

00:50:44.590 --> 00:50:46.730
And just trying to be
better and set the stakes.

00:50:46.730 --> 00:50:50.150
And let them know, so they
wouldn't have that burden,

00:50:50.150 --> 00:50:53.150
where they know their child--
and I know it's a lot of blame

00:50:53.150 --> 00:50:55.400
can go on the parents while
they're in prison for what

00:50:55.400 --> 00:50:57.590
happens to the children
while they're inside--

00:50:57.590 --> 00:51:00.590
and I didn't want to be the one
that ended up on the streets.

00:51:00.590 --> 00:51:03.440
And my father when
he was interviewed

00:51:03.440 --> 00:51:06.440
for Humans of New York, he
said that I was the exception

00:51:06.440 --> 00:51:08.090
for a lot of his children.

00:51:08.090 --> 00:51:11.120
And just the fact that
he said I had a brother

00:51:11.120 --> 00:51:13.280
that I didn't even know
about, that as soon

00:51:13.280 --> 00:51:15.260
as he got in prison
about a year later,

00:51:15.260 --> 00:51:17.570
he ended up being killed
because of following

00:51:17.570 --> 00:51:18.920
in the footsteps of him.

00:51:18.920 --> 00:51:21.507
And he said, it's children like
me that should be the norm.

00:51:21.507 --> 00:51:23.090
When they have an
incarcerated parent,

00:51:23.090 --> 00:51:25.280
we should still be able
to do well, and still

00:51:25.280 --> 00:51:27.890
be able to excel, and
do things differently.

00:51:27.890 --> 00:51:30.170
So I feel like my
future is impact

00:51:30.170 --> 00:51:31.850
because it gives me a role.

00:51:31.850 --> 00:51:34.130
And it gives me,
not only which I've

00:51:34.130 --> 00:51:37.640
found my voice because of
Topeka, I found my voice truly

00:51:37.640 --> 00:51:38.690
and honestly.

00:51:38.690 --> 00:51:42.410
Because I had never spoke about
it until I came to a point

00:51:42.410 --> 00:51:45.080
where I was so destitute
and by myself and alone.

00:51:45.080 --> 00:51:46.710
And I was just hurting.

00:51:46.710 --> 00:51:50.030
And it was everybody that
my mother had left me

00:51:50.030 --> 00:51:52.100
with had passed away.

00:51:52.100 --> 00:51:53.210
So I was 18.

00:51:53.210 --> 00:51:55.560
Living by myself,
about to go to college.

00:51:55.560 --> 00:51:57.860
I was, like, there
was no one to take me.

00:51:57.860 --> 00:51:59.760
No one to help me
with that transition.

00:51:59.760 --> 00:52:01.718
And it just got to a
point where I had nothing.

00:52:01.718 --> 00:52:02.810
I didn't have any money.

00:52:02.810 --> 00:52:06.170
And it grew to the point where
I had to go and do everything

00:52:06.170 --> 00:52:07.530
by myself.

00:52:07.530 --> 00:52:09.491
So when Topeka
came, and said, hey,

00:52:09.491 --> 00:52:11.990
would you like to speak on a
panel about how it affects you?

00:52:11.990 --> 00:52:15.650
I never really thought about
how it had majorly impacted

00:52:15.650 --> 00:52:18.140
my life, and I was numb to it.

00:52:18.140 --> 00:52:21.500
And it was just I was
so succumbed to feeling,

00:52:21.500 --> 00:52:22.830
like everything was normal.

00:52:22.830 --> 00:52:24.500
Oh, I'd go visit them
in visiting rooms.

00:52:24.500 --> 00:52:26.180
I'd talk to them on the phone.

00:52:26.180 --> 00:52:29.130
It was just seeing
my vulnerability.

00:52:29.130 --> 00:52:31.160
And then realizing
that every single time

00:52:31.160 --> 00:52:33.410
I spoke it was like I was
learning something different

00:52:33.410 --> 00:52:34.190
about myself.

00:52:34.190 --> 00:52:37.220
So I feel like from an
educational standpoint,

00:52:37.220 --> 00:52:39.770
it shows that you can
practically do anything.

00:52:39.770 --> 00:52:43.550
And like Topeka said earlier,
I do a lot of stuff with grace.

00:52:43.550 --> 00:52:48.290
So it makes me feel like I'm
powerful, that I'm invincible.

00:52:48.290 --> 00:52:50.180
And it makes it really
takes me to a point

00:52:50.180 --> 00:52:52.280
where, just because you
don't have your parents,

00:52:52.280 --> 00:52:54.490
you still have that
ability to do better and go

00:52:54.490 --> 00:52:56.805
beyond what anybody can
tell you that you can do.

00:52:56.805 --> 00:52:57.305
[APPLAUSE]

00:52:57.305 --> 00:52:58.554
ANA KASPARIAN: That's amazing.

00:53:04.010 --> 00:53:06.740
So I just wanted to quickly
note on "The Young Turks,"

00:53:06.740 --> 00:53:09.110
we often bring up the
issue of white privilege,

00:53:09.110 --> 00:53:12.170
which, unfortunately, some
of our audience members

00:53:12.170 --> 00:53:13.700
get very offended about.

00:53:13.700 --> 00:53:15.770
And the reason why I'm
bringing that up right now

00:53:15.770 --> 00:53:18.620
is because these are
the types of obstacles

00:53:18.620 --> 00:53:23.840
that the disenfranchised have
to persevere through in order

00:53:23.840 --> 00:53:25.940
to become success
stories, right?

00:53:25.940 --> 00:53:28.400
These are the issues that
I think a lot of people

00:53:28.400 --> 00:53:31.610
don't realize occur, that
we have a biased justice

00:53:31.610 --> 00:53:34.160
system, that we have
certain obstacles

00:53:34.160 --> 00:53:36.860
for certain communities that
people like me don't ever

00:53:36.860 --> 00:53:37.760
have to worry about.

00:53:37.760 --> 00:53:41.030
And that's the reason why I feel
that it's important for someone

00:53:41.030 --> 00:53:43.340
like me to be an ally, to
hear stories like yours,

00:53:43.340 --> 00:53:46.460
and do what I can to fight
to reform the justice

00:53:46.460 --> 00:53:48.140
system that we have right now.

00:53:48.140 --> 00:53:50.630
If there's one final thing
that you would want everyone

00:53:50.630 --> 00:53:53.540
to know about how all
of this has impacted you

00:53:53.540 --> 00:53:57.059
and your relationship with
your family, what would it be?

00:53:57.059 --> 00:53:59.600
KENDIA RILEY: So I think, and
especially over the last couple

00:53:59.600 --> 00:54:03.560
of days, that just separating
a mother from her daughter

00:54:03.560 --> 00:54:06.620
or father from her daughter
is really just rifting.

00:54:06.620 --> 00:54:08.900
And like I said earlier,
it's really numbing.

00:54:08.900 --> 00:54:11.450
Where you get to
this point that you

00:54:11.450 --> 00:54:14.900
want to know each other so well,
and it seems so impossible,

00:54:14.900 --> 00:54:19.240
because there's so many physical
limitations and monetary--

00:54:19.240 --> 00:54:24.770
it's just so much stuff where it
takes you away from really ever

00:54:24.770 --> 00:54:26.900
having that capability
to establish

00:54:26.900 --> 00:54:29.900
a real physical relationship.

00:54:29.900 --> 00:54:35.750
And just the idea that, if
you're arguing, if you're sad,

00:54:35.750 --> 00:54:39.084
or you're having just a
debate, or just a bad day,

00:54:39.084 --> 00:54:41.750
there's no way that you can just
hop up and say, I'm going to go

00:54:41.750 --> 00:54:43.340
visit my mom.

00:54:43.340 --> 00:54:45.710
You have to sit on
the phone, and then

00:54:45.710 --> 00:54:50.270
from every single penny of
every second you're talking,

00:54:50.270 --> 00:54:53.390
it's going to either go to waste
or go to a really good cause

00:54:53.390 --> 00:54:54.500
of talking on the phone.

00:54:54.500 --> 00:54:58.040
And I think more
lately with my mother,

00:54:58.040 --> 00:55:01.380
it's been we have
such limited time.

00:55:01.380 --> 00:55:04.090
But it's like we're going
and talking back and forth

00:55:04.090 --> 00:55:06.590
and battling about what we know
about each other and what we

00:55:06.590 --> 00:55:07.370
don't.

00:55:07.370 --> 00:55:11.450
And just to sit back and
think, if you were home,

00:55:11.450 --> 00:55:12.950
we wouldn't have to do this.

00:55:12.950 --> 00:55:15.920
Or to think about other
daughters that might not

00:55:15.920 --> 00:55:18.170
have the maturity that
I have or might not

00:55:18.170 --> 00:55:20.960
have that ability to even talk.

00:55:20.960 --> 00:55:24.770
And I just think that it's
unfair to the children,

00:55:24.770 --> 00:55:26.270
and it's just
unfair to all of us

00:55:26.270 --> 00:55:31.040
or anybody who can sit and allow
a parent to not be able to be

00:55:31.040 --> 00:55:32.960
with their child in some sense.

00:55:32.960 --> 00:55:36.290
Or just not to think about
every single stipulation

00:55:36.290 --> 00:55:38.870
that surrounds being
with their child.

00:55:38.870 --> 00:55:42.710
And just thinking, if you
have a child yourself,

00:55:42.710 --> 00:55:45.710
and you take yourself and
separate them, and put them

00:55:45.710 --> 00:55:49.520
in a room, and you guys are just
divided by these four walls,

00:55:49.520 --> 00:55:52.220
and you have no way of
communicating with each other

00:55:52.220 --> 00:55:56.030
without her sliding $1
under the door or $5

00:55:56.030 --> 00:55:57.749
for a limited amount of time.

00:55:57.749 --> 00:56:00.290
And just thinking about how you
could build that relationship

00:56:00.290 --> 00:56:02.180
or how that could taint you.

00:56:02.180 --> 00:56:04.490
And it's just not, I
don't think that when

00:56:04.490 --> 00:56:07.100
they are making the policies
and the legislation around it,

00:56:07.100 --> 00:56:09.126
they don't think about
us as the children.

00:56:09.126 --> 00:56:10.250
They think about the crime.

00:56:10.250 --> 00:56:14.120
But they don't put in place
that you're hurting us as well.

00:56:14.120 --> 00:56:17.000
While my mom's in prison,
that puts me in prison, too.

00:56:17.000 --> 00:56:18.470
So it's not just affecting them.

00:56:18.470 --> 00:56:22.147
We both have to live it
together and simultaneously.

00:56:22.147 --> 00:56:24.480
ANA KASPARIAN: Thank you so
much for sharing your story.

00:56:24.480 --> 00:56:25.146
I appreciate it.

