can touch upon the issues

01:00:54.520 --> 01:00:55.840
that Kendia was talking about.

01:00:55.840 --> 01:00:58.720
Because as a woman--
so I was a lawyer

01:00:58.720 --> 01:01:00.760
who was sentenced
to serve a 24 month

01:01:00.760 --> 01:01:02.800
sentence in the federal
prison for women

01:01:02.800 --> 01:01:03.850
in Danbury, Connecticut.

01:01:03.850 --> 01:01:06.580
OK, I was allowed
to self-report.

01:01:06.580 --> 01:01:07.300
I was a lawyer.

01:01:07.300 --> 01:01:08.510
We were treated differently.

01:01:08.510 --> 01:01:09.760
I showed up in court twice.

01:01:09.760 --> 01:01:13.060
Once to hear the charges against
me, and the other to hear what

01:01:13.060 --> 01:01:14.510
I was going to be sentenced to.

01:01:14.510 --> 01:01:18.760
I negotiated my sentence down
from 63 months to 24 months,

01:01:18.760 --> 01:01:21.910
and I went off and
served my 24 months.

01:01:21.910 --> 01:01:24.940
I happened to have older
adult children at the time.

01:01:24.940 --> 01:01:27.610
But I also had a
12-year-old daughter,

01:01:27.610 --> 01:01:30.490
who's currently a sophomore
at Spelman University, Spelman

01:01:30.490 --> 01:01:31.240
College.

01:01:31.240 --> 01:01:36.320
And I also had a baby boy who
I had just given birth to,

01:01:36.320 --> 01:01:38.110
who when I walked
into that prison-- so

01:01:38.110 --> 01:01:39.830
my whole family took
me to the prison.

01:01:39.830 --> 01:01:41.500
I, again, was
treated differently

01:01:41.500 --> 01:01:45.072
than 99% of the women that
I was incarcerated with--

01:01:45.072 --> 01:01:47.530
who had not seen their children
since they were looking out

01:01:47.530 --> 01:01:50.080
the back window of a
law enforcement vehicle,

01:01:50.080 --> 01:01:52.630
and watching their babies
being shuttled away

01:01:52.630 --> 01:01:56.180
by some other state actor, OK?

01:01:56.180 --> 01:01:59.470
And then I was in
a prison with women

01:01:59.470 --> 01:02:02.510
who had not seen their
children for six, seven,

01:02:02.510 --> 01:02:06.190
eight years, if they had
seen them at all since they

01:02:06.190 --> 01:02:07.660
had been incarcerated.

01:02:07.660 --> 01:02:10.690
And the feeling of
what that's like--

01:02:10.690 --> 01:02:12.490
my baby boy was five months old.

01:02:12.490 --> 01:02:16.810
I did not come home
until he was 2.

01:02:16.810 --> 01:02:17.920
This is Santra calling in.

01:02:17.920 --> 01:02:18.670
So I'm happy then.

01:02:18.670 --> 01:02:21.130
Because I want you to hear
her voice and not mine.

01:02:21.130 --> 01:02:22.810
But those are the
very real things

01:02:22.810 --> 01:02:25.060
that women who are
incarcerated are dealing with.

01:02:25.060 --> 01:02:28.120
And not even being
able to breathe.

01:02:28.120 --> 01:02:29.631
I want to leave us
with this point,

01:02:29.631 --> 01:02:31.630
that for a woman who
leaves her children behind,

01:02:31.630 --> 01:02:34.870
we literally have to put
our children on a shelf

01:02:34.870 --> 01:02:37.480
in order to breathe to
get through our sentence.

01:02:37.480 --> 01:02:38.293
That is criminal.

